<div id="shpr-wlk-modal" class="modal hide fade in" style="display: none; ">  
  <div class="modal-body"> 
    <h5>Shapiro-Wilks Test</h5>  
    <p> The Shapiro-Wilks Test takes a set of numbers randomly sampled
      from a population and answers the question of whether or not
      the underlying population follows a normal distribution.  The normal
      distribution can be described loosely as a set of numbers whose histogram is "bell shaped"
      but a more precise definition is that it's <em>probability density function</em> is of the form
      \[  f(x) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi \sigma ^ 2}} e^{ - \frac{(x- \mu)^2}{2 \sigma ^ 2} } \]
    </p>
    <p>
      An example of when we want to know if a set of numbers come from an underlying
      population that is normal is in linear regression.  Namely, one of the assumptions
      in linear regression is that the residuals are normally distributed.
    </p>
    <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shapiro%E2%80%93Wilk_test">For more information on the Shapiro-Wilks Test</a>    
  </div>
